Introduction¶

In this project, you will build a neural network of your own design to evaluate the MNIST dataset.

Some of the benchmark results on MNIST include can be found on Yann LeCun's page and include:

88% Lecun et al., 1998

95.3% Lecun et al., 1998

99.65% Ciresan et al., 2011

MNIST is a great dataset for sanity checking your models, since the accuracy levels achieved by large convolutional neural networks and small linear models are both quite high. This makes it important to be familiar with the data.

Load the Dataset¶

Specify your transforms as a list if you intend to . The transforms module is already loaded as transforms.

MNIST is fortunately included in the torchvision module. Then, you can create your dataset using the MNIST object from torchvision.datasets (the documentation is available here). Make sure to specify download=True!

Once your dataset is created, you'll also need to define a DataLoader from the torch.utils.data module for both the train and the test set.

Justify your preprocessing¶

In your own words, why did you choose the transforms you chose? If you didn't use any preprocessing steps, why not?

DOUBLE CLICK THIS CELL TO MODIFY

Answer:
I only used data conversion to tensor and normalisation. Data conversion to tensor is required to be used by the deep learning model to be able to use the data. And the normalisation is done since the values from range 0-255 to 0.0-1.0, this is done to bring uniformity of the data to be processed. Other transformations such as, resize, rotate, augment, translate, reposition, etc are also possible.

Explore the Dataset¶

Using matplotlib, numpy, and torch, explore the dimensions of your data.

You can view images using the show5 function defined below – it takes a data loader as an argument. Remember that normalized images will look really weird to you! You may want to try changing your transforms to view images. Typically using no transforms other than toTensor() works well for viewing – but not as well for training your network. If show5 doesn't work, go back and check your code for creating your data loaders and your training/test sets.

In [24]:
## This cell contains a function for showing 5 images from a dataloader – DO NOT CHANGE THE CONTENTS! ##
def show5(img_loader):
    dataiter = iter(img_loader)
    
    batch = next(dataiter)
    labels = batch[1][0:5]
    images = batch[0][0:5]
    for i in range(5):
        print(int(labels[i].detach()))
    
        image = images[i].numpy()
        plt.imshow(image.T.squeeze().T)
        plt.show()

Build your Neural Network¶

Using the layers in torch.nn (which has been imported as nn) and the torch.nn.functional module (imported as F), construct a neural network based on the parameters of the dataset. Use any architecture you like.

Note: If you did not flatten your tensors in your transforms or as part of your preprocessing and you are using only Linear layers, make sure to use the Flatten layer in your network!

class Proj2NN(nn.Module):
    def __init__(self, input_size, hidden_size, num_classes, criterion):
        super().__init__()
        self.criterion = criterion 
        self.all_layers =  nn.ModuleList()  
        
        flatten = nn.Flatten()  
        self.all_layers.append(flatten) 
        
        input_layer = nn.Linear(input_size, hidden_size[0])
        self.all_layers.append(input_layer) 
        
        for i in range(len(hidden_size)-1):
            hidden_layer = nn.Linear(hidden_size[i], hidden_size[i+1])
            self.all_layers.append(hidden_layer) 
        
        output_layer = nn.Linear(hidden_size[-1], num_classes)
        self.all_layers.append(output_layer) 
        if self.criterion.__class__==torch.nn.modules.loss.NLLLoss:
            self.softmax_layer = nn.LogSoftmax(dim=1) 
            
#         print(f'Total layers: {len(self.all_layers)}')
        
        
    def forward(self, x):
        i = 2 
        x = self.all_layers[0](x)        
        for layer in self.all_layers[1:-1]: 
            x = layer(x) 
            x = F.relu(x)  
            i += 1 
        x = self.all_layers[-1](x) 
        if self.criterion.__class__==torch.nn.modules.loss.NLLLoss:
#             x = F.log_softmax(x, dim=1) 
            x = self.softmax_layer(x) 
        return x


def create_model(model_type, input_size, num_classes, criterion): 
    # Create model
    model = None 
    if model_type==0:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [128, 64], num_classes, criterion, criterion)
    elif model_type==1:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [256, 128], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==2:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [512, 64], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==3:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [128, 64, 32], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==4:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [256, 128, 64], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==5:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [256, 128, 64, 32], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==6:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [512, 256, 128], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==7:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [512, 256, 128, 64, 32], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==8:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [1024, 512, 256], num_classes, criterion)
    elif model_type==9:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [1024, 512, 256, 128], num_classes, criterion)
    else:
        model = Proj2NN(input_size, [128], num_classes, criterion)
    return model

# A function defined for - Training the model
def train_model(model, trainloader, validationloader, criterion, optimizer, epochs=5, print_every=20, device='cuda'):
    # Initialise the common variables used in the training process
    train_loss_rec = [] 
    val_loss_rec = [] 
    val_acc_rec = [] 
    
    steps = 0
    running_loss = 0
    
    # start = time.time()
    for epoch in range(epochs):
    #     ep_start = time.time()
        for pass_count, (inputs, labels) in enumerate(trainloader):
    #         bt_start = time.time()
            steps += 1
            # Move input and label tensors to the default device
            inputs, labels = inputs.to(device), labels.to(device)
#             print(f'Train: epoch:{epoch}, pass_count:{pass_count}, labels len:{len(labels)}') 

            outputs = model(inputs) 
#             print(labels.unique(), outputs.unique()) 
            loss = criterion(outputs, labels)

            optimizer.zero_grad()
            loss.backward()
            optimizer.step()

            running_loss += loss.item()
            
            
            # Model validation after n batches
            if steps % print_every == 0:
                validation_loss = 0
                accuracy = 0
                model.eval()
                with torch.no_grad():
                    for test_pass_count, (test_inputs, test_labels) in enumerate(validationloader):
                        test_inputs, test_labels = test_inputs.to(device), test_labels.to(device)
#                         print(f'Val: epoch:{epoch}, test_pass_count:{test_pass_count}, labels len:{len(test_labels)}') 
                        test_outputs = model(test_inputs)
                        batch_loss = criterion(test_outputs, test_labels)

                        validation_loss += batch_loss.item()

                        ## Calculate accuracy
                        ps = torch.exp(test_outputs)
                        top_p, top_class = ps.topk(1, dim=1)
                        equals = top_class == test_labels.view(*top_class.shape)
                        accuracy += torch.mean(equals.type(torch.FloatTensor)).item()
                        
#                         _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
#                         total += labels.size(0)
#                         correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

                print(f"Epoch {epoch+1}/{epochs}.. "
                      f"Train loss: {running_loss/print_every:.4f}.. "
                      f"Validation loss: {validation_loss/len(validationloader):.4f}.. "
                      f"Validation accuracy: {(accuracy/len(validationloader))*100:.2f}")

                train_loss_rec.append(running_loss/print_every)  
                val_loss_rec.append(validation_loss/len(validationloader))
                val_acc_rec.append((accuracy/len(validationloader))*100)
                running_loss = 0
                model.train()
#                 save_model(model, model_type, model_name, num_output, criterion, optimizer, train_data)

    #         print(f"Total batch time: {(time.time() - bt_start):.3f} seconds\n")
    #     print(f"Total epoch time: {(time.time() - ep_start):.3f} seconds")            
    # print(f"Total training time: {(time.time() - start):.3f} seconds")
    return train_loss_rec, val_loss_rec, val_acc_rec

If you use a less common loss function, please note why you chose that loss function in a comment.

Anser: I choose CrossEntropyLoss, however the NLLLoss could be used. NLLLoss need the softmax to employ manually where the CrossEntropyLoss automatically does that. And both of these loss functions provide the probability scores for a prediction associated to each of the label.

Running your Neural Network¶

Use whatever method you like to train your neural network, and ensure you record the average loss at each epoch. Don't forget to use torch.device() and the .to() method for both your model and your data if you are using GPU!

If you want to print your loss during each epoch, you can use the enumerate function and print the loss after a set number of batches. 250 batches works well for most people!

Testing your model¶

Using the previously created DataLoader for the test set, compute the percentage of correct predictions using the highest probability prediction.

If your accuracy is over 90%, great work, but see if you can push a bit further! If your accuracy is under 90%, you'll need to make improvements. Go back and check your model architecture, loss function, and optimizer to make sure they're appropriate for an image classification task.

In [43]:
## YOUR CODE HERE ##
# Testing the model
model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    correct = 0
    total = 0
    for images, labels in test_loader:
        images = images.view(-1, 28*28)
        # Move input and label tensors to the default device
        images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
        outputs = model(images)
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        total += labels.size(0)
        correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

    print(f'Accuracy of the model on the 10000 test images: {100 * correct / total:.2f}%')
    test_scors = pd.DataFrame({'Test Acc':[correct / total]})

# Testing the modified model
model.eval()
with torch.no_grad():
    correct = 0
    total = 0
    for images, labels in test_loader:
        images = images.view(-1, 28*28)
        # Move input and label tensors to the default device
        images, labels = images.to(device), labels.to(device)
        outputs = model(images)
        _, predicted = torch.max(outputs.data, 1)
        total += labels.size(0)
        correct += (predicted == labels).sum().item()

    print(f'Accuracy of the model on the 10000 test images: {100 * correct / total:.2f}%')
    test_scors = pd.DataFrame({'Test Acc':[correct / total]})
